    "instruction": "Read metric.csv and trace.csv. For metric.csv, return: 1) list of distinct cmdb_id values and their counts; 2) list of distinct kpi_name values and their counts (limit to top 20); 3) overall timestamp min and max; 4) the first 5 rows. For trace.csv, return: 1) list of distinct cmdb_id values and their counts; 2) list of distinct trace_name values and their counts (limit to top 20); 3) overall timestamp min and max; 4) the first 5 rows. Keep outputs compact and textual."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step (Executor output) scanned metric.csv and trace.csv. From metric.csv: there are many components (db_001..db_013, docker_001..docker_008, os_021/os_022, etc.) and many KPI names (Page_pi, Page_po, Memory_used_pct, Disk_*, CPU_*, ss_total, Agent_ping, Incoming/Outgoing_network_traffic, etc.). Metric timestamps span 2020-04-11 05:00:00+08:00 to 2020-04-11 06:00:00+08:00, so the failure window (2020-04-11 05:30–06:00) is contained within the available metric data. From trace.csv: trace records are available for 2020-04-11 05:30:00+08:00 to 2020-04-11 05:59:00+08:00 and include trace names like trace.from_os_022.remoteprocess.* and many trace.self.* features; traces appear for docker_001..docker_004 and some os_02x. This is sufficient to proceed to the preprocessing stage. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next required step is to compute global thresholds for each candidate 'component-KPI' time series using the full available series (NOT filtered to the incident window). We should compute global percentiles (e.g., P95 and P5) per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) for all candidate root-cause components present in metric.csv, and return a compact summary so we can later filter to the incident window and detect anomalies. Derived: metric data covers the failure window; traces cover the incident window and include relationships involving os_022 -> docker_001, which may be relevant later. No faults identified yet because thresholds not computed.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For metric.csv, consider only rows whose cmdb_id belongs to the allowed root-cause component lists (node-level: os_001..os_022; container-level: docker_001..docker_008; service-level: db_001..db_013) and that actually appear in the file. For each unique (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pair, compute global statistics across the entire available series: count, min(timestamp), max(timestamp), P95(value) and P5(value). Return a compact table sorted by P95 descending and limited to the top 20 rows. Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, p95_value, p5_value. Do not filter by the incident time window yet. Keep output textual and compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds (P95 and P5) for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) across the full available series. Top global P95 breaches are for many os_* nodes' Shared_memory and several DB KPIs (e.g., db_003 tnsping_result_time, db_* Logic_Read_Per_Sec, Redo_Per_Sec). These are global baselines (not yet filtered to the incident window). Next, per the workflow we must extract metric data within the incident window (2020-04-11 05:30:00 to 2020-04-11 06:00:00, UTC+8) and detect anomalies relative to the previously computed global thresholds. The goal of the next step is to identify which component-KPIs show consecutive anomaly points during the window and rank candidates by anomaly count and severity. No fault or root cause determined yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter metric.csv rows to the incident window: 2020-04-11 05:30:00 (UTC+8) <= timestamp < 2020-04-11 06:00:00 (UTC+8). Using the precomputed global thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) (P95 and P5), detect anomaly points in that window where value >= P95 (mark as 'high') or value <= P5 (mark as 'low'). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) that has >=1 anomaly point in the window, produce a compact summary table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp(UTC+8), latest_anomaly_timestamp(UTC+8), p95_value, p5_value, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, breach_type ('high' if max_value_in_window>=p95_value else 'low' if min_value_in_window<=p5_value else 'none'), severity (for 'high' use max_value_in_window / p95_value; for 'low' use p5_value / min_value_in_window; otherwise 0). Sort by anomaly_count desc then severity desc and return top 20 rows. Keep output textual and compact." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global thresholds and detected many anomalies inside the incident window (2020-04-11 05:30–06:00 UTC+8). Top anomalies by count and severity include node-level Disk_svctm on os_002 (severity ~81.6) and os_020 (36.6), node-level Disk_io_util on os_019 (severity ~20.4), and several DB KPIs (e.g., db_011 TPS_Per_Sec and User_Commit with severity 20). According to the workflow, the next step is fault identification: convert these anomaly points into consecutive fault intervals and filter out isolated spikes and weak breaches (e.g., breaches that are not significantly beyond the threshold). This will let us determine which components experienced sustained faults and which are likely root-cause candidates. No final root cause chosen yet because we must identify sustained faults and compare cross-level severity before tracing call chains.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the top anomalous (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs (use the anomaly_summary list produced previously; limit to top 20 by anomaly_count then severity):\n1) Scan metric.csv filtered to the incident window 2020-04-11 05:30:00+08:00 <= timestamp < 2020-04-11 06:00:00+08:00 for each pair.\n2) Identify consecutive anomaly runs where value >= global P95 (mark 'high') or value <= global P5 (mark 'low'). Consecutive means adjacent minute timestamps with anomalies; report each pair's longest consecutive anomalous run.\n3) For each pair return a compact row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, breach_type (high/low), run_start_timestamp(UTC+8), run_end_timestamp(UTC+8), run_length_minutes, max_value_in_run, min_value_in_run, p95_value, p5_value, severity (use max/p95 for 'high', or p5/min for 'low'), significant_breach (True if severity >= 1.5), and a short note if run_length==30 (indicates full-window sustained). \n4) Sort results by significant_breach desc, then severity desc, then run_length desc and return top 20 rows in textual tabular form. Keep output compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We identified many sustained metric faults in the incident window (2020-04-11 05:30–06:00 UTC+8). Most prominent: db_012 - ACS sustained HIGH for the entire 30-minute window (severity 2.0), and db_006 showing multi-KPI HIGH runs (Sess_Active and Login_Per_Sec) with high severity. Several DB KPIs show elevated activity or drops; concurrently, many OS/node disk KPIs (Disk_svctm, Disk_io_util, Disk_wr_ios) show LOW or zero values on multiple os_* nodes (os_002, os_020, os_006, os_019, etc.). According to the workflow, we must now use traces to localize the root-cause component among multiple candidate DB and node faults — specifically, we need to see which faulty DB or container/node is the downstream faulty component in trace call chains and whether trace latencies or error rates point to a particular component/time. No final root cause yet because trace-level correlation has not been examined.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter trace.csv to the incident window 2020-04-11 05:30:00 (UTC+8) <= timestamp < 2020-04-11 06:00:00 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: count, earliest_timestamp(UTC+8), latest_timestamp(UTC+8), mean(value), p95(value). Return rows where trace_name contains any of: 'remoteprocess', 'jdbc', 'csf', 'flyremote', 'trace.self' (case-sensitive as in file). Sort the results by p95(value) descending and return the top 20 rows with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, mean_value, p95_value. Keep output compact and textual."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing, global-threshold calculation, anomaly detection, and fault identification. Key findings so far: many sustained anomalies in the incident window (2020-04-11 05:30–06:00 UTC+8). The most prominent metric faults are: db_012 (ACS) sustained HIGH across the full 30-minute window (severity 2.0, start 05:30), db_006 (Sess_Active and Login_Per_Sec) with significant HIGH runs starting mid-window (05:36–05:46), multiple DB KPIs with short-to-medium HIGH runs, and many node OS disk KPIs (Disk_svctm, Disk_io_util, Disk_wr_ios) exhibiting LOW or zero runs across multiple nodes (os_002, os_020, os_006, os_019, etc.). Trace data shows very high jdbc.row_count and local.row_count on docker_001..docker_004 during the same window, indicating heavy DB traffic from those containers. According to the localization rules, when multiple levels show faults, we should prefer the level with the most significant deviation from thresholds. From prior anomaly aggregates, some node-level disk metrics showed very large deviations (e.g., a Disk_svctm entry with severity ~81.6), which is much larger than the service-level DB severities (~2.0). However, we need an aggregated, compact view per candidate component (count of faulty KPIs, earliest fault start, and max severity) to pick the most likely root-cause component and occurrence time. Thus we are not yet ready to conclude the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the fault-run summary table already stored in the kernel (the consecutive-run results for top anomalies), aggregate by cmdb_id to produce a compact candidate list. For each cmdb_id compute: 1) level ('node' if cmdb_id starts with 'os_', 'container' if 'docker_', 'service' if 'db_'); 2) num_faulty_kpis (count of distinct kpi_name with at least one run); 3) earliest_fault_start (UTC+8) among its runs; 4) max_severity across its runs (ignore NaN severity but report a flag if any run had NaN due to p5==0); 5) any_full_window_sustained (True if any run_length_minutes == 30); 6) representative_kpi (the kpi_name having the max_severity). Return the top 20 cmdb_id rows sorted by max_severity desc, then num_faulty_kpis desc. Include columns: cmdb_id, level, num_faulty_kpis, earliest_fault_start, max_severity, has_nan_severity, any_full_window_sustained, representative_kpi. Keep output textual and compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated fault runs and produced a ranked candidate list per component. What has been done: global thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi) were computed; metric anomalies in the incident window (2020-04-11 05:30–06:00 UTC+8) were detected; consecutive anomalous runs were identified and summarized; components were aggregated to produce candidate ranking including level, number of faulty KPIs, earliest fault start, max severity, presence of NaN severities (p5==0), and whether any run sustained the full 30 minutes. What can be derived so far: two strong service-level candidates (db_012 — ACS sustained high for the entire 30-minute window with severity 2.0 starting at 05:30; db_006 — multiple KPI breaches starting ~05:36 with severity 2.0) and multiple node-level disk anomalies across several os_* nodes (some with extremely large numeric severity in earlier anomaly counts and others with min=0 yielding NaN severity). Traces show heavy jdbc/local row counts on docker_001..docker_004 during the same window, indicating high DB traffic. We have not yet localized the single root cause: node-level metrics have the largest numeric deviations in some cases (suggesting possible IO issues) while db_012 shows a full-window sustained service anomaly starting at 05:30. According to the localization rules, when multiple levels show faults we must (1) compare deviation magnitudes and (2) use traces to determine downstream faulty service/container if multiple same-level candidates exist. Therefore we need trace-level latency/error signals (jdbc duration_p95/error_rate) per container to see which downstream service/container experienced elevated DB call latency or errors that would point to a particular DB instance or an infrastructure issue. No final root cause declared yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter trace.csv to the incident window 2020-04-11 05:30:00 (UTC+8) <= timestamp < 2020-04-11 06:00:00 (UTC+8). For trace_names: 'trace.self.jdbc.duration_mean', 'trace.self.jdbc.duration_p95', and 'trace.self.jdbc.error_rate' compute per cmdb_id: count, earliest_timestamp(UTC+8), latest_timestamp(UTC+8), mean(value), and p95(value). Return rows where count>0, sorted by p95(value) descending, limited to top 20. Produce a compact textual table with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, mean_value, p95_value."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace JDBC analysis shows elevated JDBC throughput (high row_count) on docker_001..docker_004 and moderate JDBC latency tails (p95 ~2.5–3.3 ms) but no errors (error_rate == 0) during 2020-04-11 05:30–06:00 UTC+8. Combined with the metric analysis, the strongest metric-level candidates are: db_012 (ACS) with a full-window sustained HIGH starting 05:30 (severity 2.0) and db_006 with multiple KPI breaches starting ~05:36 (severity 2.0). Many os_* nodes show disk KPI abnormalities (Disk_svctm, Disk_io_util, Disk_wr_ios) including values dropping to zero (p5==0 causing NaN severity) across os_002, os_006, os_019, os_020, etc. According to localization rules, when both service-level and node-level faults exist we should prefer the level with the most significant deviation and then use traces to pick the downstream faulty component among same-level candidates. Current traces show high load (row counts) from several containers to DB but no JDBC errors; we still lack evidence tying the sustained db_012 ACS anomaly to a specific container or proving an underlying infrastructure (disk IO) fault is the primary cause. Next, we need to inspect inter-service/inter-node trace metrics (trace names containing 'from_') in the incident window to see which downstream calls show elevated duration or p95 and whether those point to a particular DB instance or node at/near 05:30. This will help decide whether the root cause is service-level (db_012 or db_006) or node-level (one of the os_*).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter trace.csv to the incident window 2020-04-11 05:30:00 (UTC+8) <= timestamp < 2020-04-11 06:00:00 (UTC+8). Select rows where trace_name contains the substring 'from_' (case-sensitive). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: count, earliest_timestamp(UTC+8), latest_timestamp(UTC+8), mean(value), and p95(value). Return the top 20 rows sorted by p95(value) descending with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, mean_value, p95_value. Keep output compact and textual."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi), filtered metrics to the incident window (2020-04-11 05:30–06:00 UTC+8), detected anomalies, identified consecutive fault runs, aggregated fault runs per component, and analyzed traces. Key findings so far: (1) db_012 - ACS shows a sustained HIGH run covering the full 30-minute window starting at 05:30 (severity 2.0) — highest sustained service-level anomaly; (2) db_006 shows multiple service KPI breaches (Sess_Active, Login_Per_Sec) starting ~05:36 with severity 2.0; (3) many node-level disk KPIs (os_002, os_006, os_019, os_020, etc.) show abnormal Disk_svctm/Disk_io_util/Disk_wr_ios behavior, in some cases dropping to zero (p5==0) or showing very large spikes (earlier anomaly list showed os_002 Disk_svctm max_in_window ≫ p95, severity ~81.6); (4) traces show high jdbc/local row counts on docker_001..docker_004 and elevated remoteprocess durations from os_021/os_022 to several containers (p95 up to ~2.3s) — indicating heavy upstream traffic and some remote-call latency. What remains: we must decide the single root cause component, exact occurrence time, and reason. Per localization rules, we should (a) compare earliest fault times and severity among top candidates and (b) use traces to link downstream faulty components. Right now, db_012 (full-window from 05:30) and node-level disk anomalies (os_002 with extreme spike and also zeros) are the strongest candidates but conflict in level. We need per-minute series and exact first anomaly timestamp+severity for the prime candidates so we can pick the predominant root-cause level and component. No final root cause is declared yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For precise localization, extract per-minute metric rows in the incident window 2020-04-11 05:30:00 (UTC+8) <= timestamp < 2020-04-11 06:00:00 (UTC+8) for these three candidate pairs: 1) db_012 - ACS, 2) db_006 - Sess_Active, 3) os_002 - Disk_svctm. For each pair do the following and return a compact textual result: \n1) A one-line summary with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, earliest_timestamp_in_window(UTC+8), earliest_anomaly_timestamp(UTC+8) relative to the global thresholds (first minute where value >= P95 or <= P5), anomaly_type (high/low), run_start_of_first_run, run_length_minutes_of_first_run, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5, computed_severity (use max/p95 for 'high', p5/min for 'low'; mark severity as NaN if p5==0 and type=='low').\n2) Up to 10 per-minute rows for that pair within the window (columns: ts_local(UTC+8), timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p95, p5, anomaly_flag) showing the anomaly flag for each row. Limit per-pair rows to 10 to keep output bounded.\nReturn results for the three pairs only, in textual/tabular form. Keep outputs compact."
}

